	• Low Severity: Historical system instability, OEM game entitlement missing
Root Cause Analysis
	• Primary Root Cause:
		○ Third-party driver automation tools installed incompatible drivers
		○ Multiple repair attempts modified servicing infrastructure
		○ Driver mismatch between generic and OEM-specific drivers
	• Resulting Issues:
		○ Windows servicing stack corruption
		○ Windows Update pipeline failure
		○ Hardware feature integration degradation
	• Secondary Root Cause:
		○ OEM entitlement loss tied to factory image and hardware identity validation
Resolution Steps
Phase 1 — Clean Windows Installation
	• Full system wipe, clean Windows 11 installation
	• Official WLAN driver installed for network connectivity
	• Windows activation restored with verified license key
	• BitLocker encryption verified
Phase 2 — User and System Configuration
	• Admin and local accounts created
	• Base OS apps installed
	• Browsers installed: Edge, Opera
	• Usability/performance optimizations applied
Phase 3 — System Servicing and Update Validation
	• Integrity checks: sfc /scannow, chkdsk /f /r
	• Advanced DISM servicing: /ScanHealth, /RestoreHealth, /StartComponentCleanup
	• Windows Update service reset
	• Network stack reset: netsh winsock reset, netsh int ip reset, ipconfig /flushdns
Phase 4 — Controlled Driver Installation
	• Drivers installed only from trusted sources: Windows Update, OEM platform utilities, official OEM support
	• Avoided all third-party driver automation tools
Phase 5 — Additional Support Actions
	• Investigated OEM-bound game entitlement
	• Confirmed non-critical, no system impact
Resolved Issues
	• Windows Update servicing failures
	• System instability and freezes
	• Display blanking
	• Audio subsystem loss
	• Driver stack inconsistencies
	• Remaining Open Item: OEM game entitlement recovery (non-blocking)
Post-Repair Validation
	• Windows Update installs verified (feature and security updates)
	• System stable over multiple reboots
	• Audio fully functional
	• No crashes, freezes, or servicing failures
	• Stable under productivity and development workloads
	• System stability: Excellent
Preventive Recommendations
	• Driver Installation Governance: Install drivers only from trusted sources; avoid third-party automation tools
	• Servicing Integrity Protection: Treat Windows Update failures as critical indicators; avoid aggressive servicing stack modifications
	• Stability Preservation: Introduce performance tuning only after servicing baseline validation
	• Backup and Recovery: Create system image backups at stable configuration milestones; maintain BitLocker recovery key backups
Final Conclusion
Laptop II successfully completed full Windows reinstallation and controlled reconfiguration, restoring complete system stability, servicing integrity, and hardware/software functionality.
All previous driver-induced servicing stack corruption and Windows Update failures have been fully remediated.
The system is now stable, secure, and ready for long-term operational use.
